channel.title: Interleaved RSS Feed
channel.description: This is an interleaved feed of the most recent entries from each RSS source, skipping any feeds with errors.

item.title: Sewage Spill Temporarily Closes Two Los Angeles Beaches
item.description: An estimated 15,000 gallons of sewage spilled into a creek this weekend, closing Venice and Dockweiler State Beaches, officials said. But on Tuesday morning, locals stuck to their beach routines.

item.title: An Unbending Leader’s Crackdown Rains Carnage on Bangladesh
item.description: Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina’s deadly response to student-led protests has grown into the biggest challenge ever to her dominance.

item.title: Florida is supposed to be a boomer paradise, but it didn’t even crack the top five best states for retirement
item.description: Billionaires like Jeff Bezos have resettled in Florida but other retirees have soured on the sunshine state

item.title: Bob Menendez Will Resign From Senate, Avoiding an Ugly, Intraparty Battle
item.description: Senator Robert Menendez of New Jersey was facing a possible expulsion vote after his conviction on federal corruption charges last week.

item.title: Reality Show Contestant Apologizes After Eating Protected Bird in New Zealand
item.description: A contestant on the reality show “Race to Survive: New Zealand” killed and ate a weka during filming. The contestant, who said he was hungry, has apologized for “disrespecting New Zealand.”

item.title: Sergey Brin is using money from selling his Tesla shares to bankroll a startup developing hallucinogenic mental-health treatments
item.description: The Google cofounder invested $500,000 in Tesla in 2008.

item.title: How to Get Compensated If You Were Caught in the CrowdStrike Outage
item.description: Air travelers paying for last-minute lodging and other expenses are entitled to be reimbursed if their flight was impacted by an event in the airline’s control, like the CrowdStrike failure. Here’s how to get your money back.

item.title: Middle East Crisis: Israeli Forces Strike in Humanitarian Zone; Scores Reported Killed
item.description: The Israeli military warned Gazans to leave part of what it had previously designated as a relatively safe area in Khan Younis, saying Hamas had launched rockets from there.

item.title: Kamala Harris has a history of opposing trade deals that are bad for workers and the environment
item.description: One expert calls Harris' approach to trade policy that of a "centrist Democrat" who is unwilling to compromise certain priorities.

item.title: The Secret Service Has Failed Americans Since the Trump Shooting
item.description: Conspiracy theorists have been able to fill the information void with their own versions of the truth.

item.title: Netanyahu Seeks Support in U.S. Visit, but Will Find a Nation Distracted
item.description: Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel is to meet President Biden and address Congress this week, swapping one political maelstrom at home for another in Washington.

item.title: With homebuying ‘more expensive than ever,’ buyers are backing out of deals at a record pace
item.description: Last month saw more in-contract sales canceled than any June on record, according to Redfin.

item.title: Katharine Graham’s Fabled Washington Home Is Kept Empty by a 22-Year Battle
item.description: The home of the former Washington Post publisher was once a hub of power and comity. But after an “insane” renovation spat, its new owner is looking to sell.

item.title: Writing Helped Her Realize She Was a Woman. It Also Made Her Famous.
item.description: Camila Sosa Villada, an Argentine transgender author, first inhabited a female voice in stories she wrote as a child. Now her novels are translated in more than 20 languages and being adapted for the screen.

item.title: Tesla’s humanoid robots are going to arrive a bit later than Elon Musk initially promised
item.description: Tesla’s CEO has a history of being overly optimistic on dates.
